<Guide
  title="Multi-pane layouts — Gallager"
  description="Splitting, resizing and persisting terminal layouts on the Mac, and how the iPhone mirrors them."
  heroTitle="Multi-pane layouts"
  lede="Real tmux panes in native windows: split and arrange them on the Mac, and your iPhone mirrors the layout live."
>
  <h2>On the Mac</h2>
  <p>
    Every pane is a real tmux pane rendered in a native window. Split horizontally or
    vertically, resize by dragging, reorder panes, and spread sessions across as many
    windows as you like. Agents keep running inside tmux regardless of what the windows
    are doing.
  </p>

  <h2>Layouts persist per project</h2>
  <p>
    Each project folder remembers its workbench: the split arrangement, open file tabs,
    browser tabs and sidebar state. It's saved automatically as you work and restored
    the next time you open that folder — no "save layout" button to remember.
  </p>

  <h2>On the iPhone</h2>
  <p>
    The phone live-mirrors the Mac's layout: the same panes, tiled the same way,
    updating as the arrangement changes. Tap a pane to focus and type into it, and
    split panes right from the phone. Resizing and reordering are done on the Mac —
    the mirror follows instantly.
  </p>

  <h2>Viewing another Mac</h2>
  <p>
    A Mac can also be the remote viewer for another Mac. In that case the viewer keeps
    its own layout per remote folder — browser tabs and split arrangement — stored
    locally on the viewing machine, so your setup at the desk and on the laptop can
    differ without fighting each other.
  </p>
</Guide>
